    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>The order of reactivity of the compounds $$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Br}, \\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}\\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right) \\mathrm{Br}, \\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right) \\mathrm{Br}$$ and $$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{C}\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)\\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right) \\mathrm{Br}$$ in $$\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 2$$ reaction is</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltbqhbd5/f68a1714-512f-4731-b061-dca87750d2df/11fbc9b0-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqhbd7.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltbqhbd5/f68a1714-512f-4731-b061-dca87750d2df/11fbc9b0-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqhbd7.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2021 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 12 English Option 1\">"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltbqjanp/818a0a48-8442-4fa2-b58e-dd0d8e97a804/490dfe50-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqjanq.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltbqjanp/818a0a48-8442-4fa2-b58e-dd0d8e97a804/490dfe50-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqjanq.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2021 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 12 English Option 2\">"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltbqkoi6/8c4aca90-afc9-4991-8fae-56644e77ec4d/6f8f52e0-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqkoi7.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltbqkoi6/8c4aca90-afc9-4991-8fae-56644e77ec4d/6f8f52e0-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqkoi7.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2021 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 12 English Option 3\">"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltbqlseo/31f5135f-5d64-40fd-b82e-9720ae4a6cc1/8e626810-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqlsep.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltbqlseo/31f5135f-5d64-40fd-b82e-9720ae4a6cc1/8e626810-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqlsep.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2021 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 12 English Option 4\">"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The order of reactivity of given compounds in $$\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 2$$ reaction is</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltbqnfni/e13e4ef1-8caf-4ee4-936e-854cc9161a3d/bc2641e0-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqnfnj.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltbqnfni/e13e4ef1-8caf-4ee4-936e-854cc9161a3d/bc2641e0-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqnfnj.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2021 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 12 English Explanation 1\"></p>\n<p>For $$\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 2$$ reaction, the order of reaction is inversely proportional to steric hinderance cause by bulky groups.</p>\n<p>In <img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltbqp6bg/38445862-69e7-4fd5-8000-1dcbcbcbb7fb/ec8e87c0-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqp6bh.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltbqp6bg/38445862-69e7-4fd5-8000-1dcbcbcbb7fb/ec8e87c0-d97c-11ee-8474-a73dd823a51b/file-1ltbqp6bh.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2021 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 12 English Explanation 2\"> there are two bulky groups are present i.e. benzene group and one methyl group which provide steric hinderance for the attack of nucleophile. Hence, it is least reactive while in $$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Br}$$ ($$1^{\\circ}$$ halide), the attack of nucleophile is easier due to less steric hinderance.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2021,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2021",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Which of the following halide shows highest reactivity towards $$\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 1$$ reaction?</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{I}$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{Cl}$$"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The order of reactivity of halides for $$S_N 1$$ reaction is $$3^{\\circ}&gt;2^{\\circ}&gt;1^{\\circ}$$ as the stability of carbocation formed in $$\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 1$$ will be highest for $$3^{\\circ}$$ and lowest for $$1^{\\circ}$$. Here, $$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}$$ will show highest reactivity for $$\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 1$$ mechanism as the carbocation left after removel of $$\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$$ is resonance stablised.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lth4y9v3/21c05f88-e150-4666-b9be-a3ad2b8f432e/94a20ff0-dc74-11ee-ae06-d5d53a247af4/file-1lth4y9x6.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lth4y9v3/21c05f88-e150-4666-b9be-a3ad2b8f432e/94a20ff0-dc74-11ee-ae06-d5d53a247af4/file-1lth4y9x6.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2020 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 11 English Explanation\"></p>\n<p>So, $$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}$$ will show highest reactivity towards $$S_N 1$$ reaction.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2020,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2020",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Which of the following halide undergoes hydrolysis on warming with water/aqueous $$\\mathrm{NaOH}$$ ?</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltu2z17a/88b55067-80fb-4852-b4bf-d51a40855e45/07ef6050-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu2z17b.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltu2z17a/88b55067-80fb-4852-b4bf-d51a40855e45/07ef6050-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu2z17b.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 9 English Option 1\">"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltu30f4n/26fdbfc6-ed94-4134-a68b-6eb2b009964c/2e80ba70-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu30f4o.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltu30f4n/26fdbfc6-ed94-4134-a68b-6eb2b009964c/2e80ba70-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu30f4o.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 9 English Option 2\">"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltu30scn/67ca7d7d-0119-45b8-bcbf-0fec845f22ba/38b77970-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu30sco.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltu30scn/67ca7d7d-0119-45b8-bcbf-0fec845f22ba/38b77970-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu30sco.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 9 English Option 3\">"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltu317fw/619ca184-6168-481a-8d72-145d1d4666ea/445fa2c0-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu317fx.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltu317fw/619ca184-6168-481a-8d72-145d1d4666ea/445fa2c0-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu317fx.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 9 English Option 4\">"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Option (d), i.e. 2, 4, 6 trinitrochlorobenzene readily undergoes hydrolysis on warming with water/aqueous $$\\mathrm{NaOH}$$. Presence of electron withdrawing groups such as $$-\\mathrm{NO}_2$$ at $$Q$$ and p-position of haloarenes with respect to halogen greatly activates the halogen towards nucleophilic substitution</p>\n<p>Reaction of 2,4,6-trinitrochlorobenzene with warm water is as follows :</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltu32m0a/7396bbc6-089e-4893-bd29-63573ca1837d/6b6f54a0-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu32m0b.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltu32m0a/7396bbc6-089e-4893-bd29-63573ca1837d/6b6f54a0-e393-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu32m0b.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 9 English Explanation\"></p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2019,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2019",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>The compound having longest C$$-$$Cl bond is</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltu3dtrj/efc22fe8-761e-4ba3-8403-9872cc1e9b1c/a353d7f0-e394-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu3dtrk.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltu3dtrj/efc22fe8-761e-4ba3-8403-9872cc1e9b1c/a353d7f0-e394-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu3dtrk.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 10 English Option 1\">"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltu3ec2k/ee8372c1-829b-40b6-a2d4-070ac523c7b7/b177fdc0-e394-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu3ec2l.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltu3ec2k/ee8372c1-829b-40b6-a2d4-070ac523c7b7/b177fdc0-e394-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu3ec2l.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 10 English Option 2\">"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltu3eq6z/67506e10-5703-422c-a8e0-56c5ad26e786/bc60ceb0-e394-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu3eq70.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltu3eq6z/67506e10-5703-422c-a8e0-56c5ad26e786/bc60ceb0-e394-11ee-aa70-a921f3f219f8/file-1ltu3eq70.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 10 English Option 3\">"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{CH_2=CH-Cl}$$"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "B"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The compound having longest $$\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{Cl}$$ bond is option (b), i.e. 3-chlorocyclohex-1-ene. In this molecule, carbon bond is $$s p^3$$-hybridised having $$25 \\% s$$-character. Option (a), (c) and (d) have $$s p^2$$ hybridised $$\\mathrm{C}$$-atom with greater $$s$$-character (i.e. $$33.3 \\%$$ s-character). $$s p^2$$-hybridised C-atom is more electronegative than $$s p^3$$-hybridised $$\\mathrm{C}$$-atom. It can hold the electron pair of the bond more tightly than $$s p^3$$-hybridised. As a result, $$\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{X}$$ bond in option (a), (c) and (d) is shorter than option (b).</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2019,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2019",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "Which of the following statements is true is case of alkyl halides?\n",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "They are polar in nature\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "They can form hydrogen bonds\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "They are highly soluble in water\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "They undergo addition reactions"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Let's analyze each option:</p>\n\n<p>$$\\textbf{Option A: They are polar in nature}$$  </p>\n\n\n<p><p>Alkyl halides have a $$\\text{C–X}$$ bond (where X is a halogen such as Cl, Br, or I).  </p></p>\n<p><p>The halogen is more electronegative than carbon, which creates a dipole in the bond.  </p></p>\n<p><p>Even though the overall molecular polarity can depend on the molecular structure, the presence of the $$\\text{C–X}$$ bond makes them polar in nature.  </p></p>\n<p><p>Therefore, Option A is true.</p></p>\n\n\n<p>$$\\textbf{Option B: They can form hydrogen bonds}$$  </p>\n\n\n<p><p>For a molecule to form hydrogen bonds, it must have a hydrogen atom attached to a highly electronegative atom like $$\\text{O}$$, $$\\text{N}$$, or $$\\text{F}$$.  </p></p>\n<p><p>In alkyl halides, the hydrogens are bonded to carbon, not to the halogen.  </p></p>\n<p><p>Hence, they do not participate in hydrogen bonding.</p></p>\n\n\n<p>$$\\textbf{Option C: They are highly soluble in water}$$  </p>\n\n\n<p><p>While the $$\\text{C–X}$$ bond is polar, alkyl halides have relatively large nonpolar hydrocarbon parts.  </p></p>\n<p><p>This makes them largely insoluble in water since water is a highly polar solvent and mixes well only with similarly polar substances.</p></p>\n\n\n<p>$$\\textbf{Option D: They undergo addition reactions}$$  </p>\n\n\n<p><p>Addition reactions typically occur with unsaturated compounds (such as alkenes or alkynes).  </p></p>\n<p><p>Alkyl halides are saturated compounds (only $$\\sigma$$ bonds) and do not undergo addition reactions under normal conditions.</p></p>\n\n<p>Given the explanations, the correct statement is:</p>\n<p>$$\\boxed{\\textbf{Option A: They are polar in nature}}$$</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2018,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2018",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "Tertiary alkyl halide is practically inert to substitution by $\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 2$ mechanism because of\n",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "insolubility\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "instability\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "inductive effect\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "steric hindrance"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The correct answer is Option D: steric hindrance.</p>\n<p>Here's why:</p>\n\n<p><p>In an $$S_N2$$ reaction, the nucleophile must approach the electrophilic carbon from behind (the side opposite the leaving group) to displace it.</p></p>\n<p><p>Tertiary alkyl halides have three bulky alkyl groups around the reactive carbon. These bulky groups create steric hindrance, which physically blocks the nucleophile from accessing the carbon center.</p></p>\n<p><p>Because the nucleophile cannot effectively approach the electrophilic center, the $$S_N2$$ reaction is significantly slowed down or doesn’t occur at all.</p></p>\n\n<p>Thus, tertiary alkyl halides are practically inert to substitution by the $$S_N2$$ mechanism due to steric hindrance.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2018,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2018",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
